<font color="#FF0000">ADVICE TO EDUCATORS</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jul  4 11:58:48 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
When addressing the Viet Nam War, it is probably sequential thinking that prompts me to suggest to educators that consideration be given the following:<br>
1. What is the maturation level of the student(s)?<br>
2. What is the time limit alloted?<br>
3. What specific subject(s)is/are to be discussed?<br>
4. What assurance does the educator have that the facts, statistics, and other supportive data is authentic and true?<br>
5. What valuable insights are there to be gained to facilitate the student's understanding of mankinds'behavior, individually and collectively, as it has manifested itself in the tangible evidence of a war that has already been fought?<br>
6. What understanding is gained of the social, economic, political, cultural, spiritual and physical actions that precipitate the engagement in war, regulate and perpetuate its conduct and ultimately struggles to explain its consequences?<br>
7. What logic exists to justify the person's or nation's premiss that war is necessary or that war must be avoided?<br>
In a holistic vein, it is important to impress the student with the overall global view(s) of the Viet Nam War, views as diverse and opposing as the huge population of individuals that present them.  Keep alive the awareness that sacred institutions and declarations all over the world prescribe justice, fairness, and freedom, but realistically, it is too often an armed force that guarantees its implementation.  Strive to impart that costs go beyond the purchase of weaponry and that wounds go beyond the battlefield.
